Credit Card Users Churn Prediction

Problem Statement

Business Context

The Thera bank recently saw a steep decline in the number of users of their credit card, credit cards are a good source of income for banks because of different kinds of fees charged by the banks like annual fees, balance transfer fees, and cash advance fees, late payment fees, foreign transaction fees, and others. Some fees are charged to every user irrespective of usage, while others are charged under specified circumstances.

Customers leaving credit cards services would lead bank to loss, so the bank wants to analyze the data of customers and identify the customers who will leave their credit card services and reason for same so that bank could improve upon those areas

You as a Data scientist at Thera bank need to come up with a classification model that will help the bank improve its services so that customers do not renounce their credit cards

Data Description

  • CLIENTNUM: Client number. Unique identifier for the customer holding the account
  • Attrition_Flag: Internal event (customer activity) variable - if the account is closed then "Attrited Customer" else "Existing Customer"
  • Customer_Age: Age in Years
  • Gender: Gender of the account holder
  • Dependent_count: Number of dependents
  • Education_Level: Educational Qualification of the account holder - Graduate, High School, Unknown, Uneducated, College(refers to college student), Post-Graduate, Doctorate
  • Marital_Status: Marital Status of the account holder
  • Income_Category: Annual Income Category of the account holder
  • Card_Category: Type of Card
  • Months_on_book: Period of relationship with the bank (in months)
  • Total_Relationship_Count: Total no. of products held by the customer
  • Months_Inactive_12_mon: No. of months inactive in the last 12 months
  • Contacts_Count_12_mon: No. of Contacts in the last 12 months
  • Credit_Limit: Credit Limit on the Credit Card
  • Total_Revolving_Bal: Total Revolving Balance on the Credit Card
  • Avg_Open_To_Buy: Open to Buy Credit Line (Average of last 12 months)
  • Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1: Change in Transaction Amount (Q4 over Q1)
  • Total_Trans_Amt: Total Transaction Amount (Last 12 months)
  • Total_Trans_Ct: Total Transaction Count (Last 12 months)
  • Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1: Change in Transaction Count (Q4 over Q1)
  • Avg_Utilization_Ratio: Average Card Utilization Ratio

What Is a Revolving Balance?

  • If we don't pay the balance of the revolving credit account in full every month, the unpaid portion carries over to the next month. That's called a revolving balance
What is the Average Open to buy?
  • 'Open to Buy' means the amount left on your credit card to use. Now, this column represents the average of this value for the last 12 months.
What is the Average utilization Ratio?
  • The Avg_Utilization_Ratio represents how much of the available credit the customer spent. This is useful for calculating credit scores.
Relation b/w Avg_Open_To_Buy, Credit_Limit and Avg_Utilization_Ratio:
  • ( Avg_Open_To_Buy / Credit_Limit ) + Avg_Utilization_Ratio = 1

# function to plot stacked bar chart
# Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart
# data: dataframe
# predictor: independent variable
# target: target variable


def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()
In[183]:
### re-usable function to Box and Hist plot distributions wrt target
#data: dataframe
#feature: dataframe for a selected column
#target : selected target column
def box_hist_plot_distribution_wrt_target(data, feature, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Hist plot Distribution W.R.T target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=feature,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Gist plot Distribution W.R.T target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=feature,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot W.R.T target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=feature, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="Spectral")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) W.R.T target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=feature,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="Spectral",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Q&A with analysis

1. How is the total transaction amount distributed?

  • Distribution of Total Transaction Amount is right skewed

2. What is the distribution of the level of education of customers?

  • Distribution of Education Level is right skewed
  • 30% of the customers are Graduate, 20% completed high school, 15% are Uneducated and 5% are post graduate and Doctarate.

3. What is the distribution of the level of income of customers?

  • Distribution of income is little right distributed
  • 35% of the customers have income less than 40K, 14% earn 80-120K, 17% earn 40-60K, 7% earn above 120K. But 10% of the customers have provided there income as 'abc'
  • abc is added as one of the income category, this needs to be treated

4. How does the change in transaction amount between Q4 and Q1 (total_ct_change_Q4_Q1) vary by the customer's account status (Attrition_Flag)?

  • Transaction done by Existing_Customers is 3 times more than Attrited_Customer between Q4 and Q1

outlier_column = ['Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1', 'Total_Trans_Amt', 'Total_Trans_Ct', 'Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1']

# to find the 25th percentile and 75th percentile for the numerical columns.
Q1 = df[outlier_column].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df[outlier_column].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1                   #Inter Quantile Range (75th percentile - 25th percentile)
lower_whisker = Q1 - 1.5*IQR    #Finding lower and upper bounds for all values. All values outside these bounds are outliers
upper_whisker = Q3 + 1.5*IQR

# Percentage of outliers in each column
((df[outlier_column] < lower_whisker) | (df[outlier_column] > upper_whisker)).sum()/df.shape[0]*100

Pre-Model Building exersice

Model can make wrong predictions as:

  1. Predicting an enrollee is looking for a job change but in reality, the enrollee is not looking for a change - Loss of resources
  2. Predicting an enrollee is not looking for a job change but the enrollee is looking for a job change - Loss of opportunity

Which case is more important?

  • Predicting an enrollee is not looking for a job change but the enrollee is looking for a job change i.e. losing on a potential candidate as the candidate will not be targeted by the HR team when he should be targeted.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negatives?

  • Company would want Recall to be maximized, greater the Recall lesser the chances of false negatives.

Model evaluation criterion

  • Lets define a utility function to collate all the metrics into a single data frame.

Let's define a function to output different metrics (including recall) on the train and test set so that we do not have to use the same code repetitively while evaluating models.

In[204]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1

        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

print("\n" "Training Performance:" "\n")
for name, model in models:
    model.fit(X_train_un, y_train_un)
    scores = recall_score(y_train_un, model.predict(X_train_un))
    print("{}: {}".format(name, scores))

print("\n" "Validation Performance:" "\n")

for name, model in models:
    model.fit(X_train_un, y_train_un)
    scores = recall_score(y_val, model.predict(X_val))
    print("{}: {}".format(name, scores))

Summary Model Building Analysis

  • Bagging, Random Forest, Gradient Boosting, Adaboost and DecisionTree were considered as 5 model
  • Applied class_weight as balanced for Bagging, Random Forest and Decision Tree to adjust weight inversely proportional to class frequencies
  • These models were being fit against training and validation with original, Over and Under sample data

Model Building - Origional Data

  • recall_score were printed for comparison
  • Gradient boosting had recall score of 0.9921 on Train and 0.9888 on Validation
  • Adaboost had 0.9825 on Train and 0.9823 on Validation
  • The difference of Train and Validation for Gradient boosting was 0.0033 and Adaboost was 0.0002

Model Building - Over Sampled Data

  • During over sampling, sampling data for train were synthetically updated from 976 to 5099 for botth "Yes" and "No" label
  • Gradient Boosting had recall score of 0.98254 for Train and 0.9770 for validation
  • Adaboost had recall score of 0.9662 for train and 0.9647 for test
  • The difference of Trai and Validation for Gradient boosting was 0.0055 and Adaboost was 0.0016

Model Building - Under Sampled Data

  • During under sampling, sampling data for train were trimmed to 976 for both "Yes" and "No" label
  • During under sampling, sampling data for train were trimmed to 976
  • Gradient Boosting had recall score of 0.97233 for Train and 0.95117 for validation
  • Adaboost had recall score of 0.94057 for train and 0.92235 for test
  • The difference of Trai and Validation for Gradient boosting was 0.0212 and Adaboost was 0.0182

Reason for choosing Model

  • After building 15 models, it was observed that both Gradient boosting and Adaboose models trained on undersampled and Gradient boosting on over sample show cased generalized performance on train and validation datasets
  • Further we will consider Gradient boosting (Over and under sampled) and Adaboosting (under sampled) for hyperparameter tuning

HyperparameterTuning

  • Hyperparameter tuning we will consider Adabooster with undersample
  • Gradient Boosting with Over and Undersample

Hyper Parameter Analysis

Tuning Adabooster with Understampled

1 Applying parameter and let it undergo RandomizedSearchCV with an CV = 5 and n_tier= 50 for 50 models training for 5 times.

  • Adabooster with under sampled provided best parameter as n_tier = 30,CV = 0.928
  • After applying suggested hyper parameter for Adaboost, we got recall score of 0.876025 on train and 0.877059 on Validation with a difference of 0.001034

Tuning Gradient Boosting with Under-sampled

  • Same process of applying parameter and let it go through RandomizedSearch with an CV = 5 and n_tier= 50 for 50 models training for 5 times.
  • GradientBoosting with Under sampled best parameter as n-tier = 125, CV = 0.937, max_feature = 0.5
  • After applying suggested hyper parameter for Gradient Boosting we got recall score of 0.92418 on train and 0.921765 on Validation with a difference of 0.002415

Tuning Gradient Boosting with Over-sampled

  • Same process of applying parameter and let it go through RandomizedSearch with an CV = 5 and n_tier= 50 for 50 models training for 5 times.

  • GradientBoosting with Over sampled best parameter as n-tier = 125, CV = 0.9866, max_feature = 0.7

  • After applying suggested hyper parameter for Gradient Boosting we got recall score of 0.907825 on train and 0.921765 with a difference of 0.01448

  • AdaBoost model trained with undersampled Data has generalised performance, but for Model Selection and Final coparison lets run Gradient boosting and Adaboost on Test data and compare.
